\begin{equation*}
   E = \frac{1}{T_0}\int\limits_{0}^{T_0} |A\cos(2\pi t/T_0 + \phi)|^2 dt
\end{equation*}
can be evaluated directly.
 Although it is possible to use a trigonometric identity, we will use Euler&#39;s
formula followed by the complex number identity \(|z+w|^2 = |z|^2  +
2\Re{e}\{ z w^* \} + |w|^2\).

 \begin{eqnarray*}
  E_T &=& \frac{1}{T_0}\int\limits_{0}^{T_0} \left | \frac{1}{2} Ae^{j((2\pi /T_0)t + \phi})
 +\frac{1}{2} Ae^{-j((2\pi /T_0)t + \phi)}\right|^2 dt\\
&=& \frac{1}{T_0}\int\limits_{0}^{T_0}   |\frac{1}{2} A|^2
  +2\Re{e}\left\{\frac{1}{2} Ae^{j((2\pi /T_0)t + \phi)}\frac{1}{2} Ae^{j((2\pi /T_0)t+ \phi)}
\right\}   + |\frac{1}{2} A|^2 dt\ &=& \frac{1}{T_0}\int\limits_{0}^{T_0}
\frac{1}{4} A^2
  +2\Re{e}\left\{\frac{1}{4} A^2e^{j((4\pi /T_0)t + 2\phi)} \right\}  +  \frac{1}{4} A^2
dt\\
 &=& \frac{1}{T_0} \frac{1}{2} A^2 T_0 + \frac{1}{T_0}\int\limits_{0}^{T_0}
  \frac{1}{2} A^2\cos((4\pi /T_0)t + 2\phi)   dt\\
&=&  \frac{1}{2} A^2
\end{eqnarray*}

Note that the integral of the cosine term is zero, being an
integral over two complete periods.</div></div>

The result in Example~<a class="flink bkimg" ref="exam-avg-power-sinusoid">&#8251;</a> can be related to the Fourier
series coefficients if we note that Euler&#39;s formula is, in fact, the Fourier
series of the sinusoid.
\begin{equation*}
   A\cos(2\pi t/T_0 + \phi) =
   \frac{1}{2} A e^{j \phi}e^{j2\pi t/T_0 }
   + \frac{1}{2} A e^{-j \phi} e^{-j2\pi t/T_0 }
\end{equation*}
 The Fourier Series has only two non-zero coefficients, \(a_1\) and \(a_{-1}\), so
an  alternate way of evaluating the average power is:
\begin{equation*}
   \sum\limits_{k=-\infty}^\infty |a_k|^2 = |a_1|^2 + |a_{-1}|^2
  = |\frac{1}{2} Ae^{j \phi}|^2 + |\frac{1}{2} Ae^{-j \phi}|^2 = \frac{1}{2} A^2
\end{equation*}
 Amazingly, this result generalizes to the case where the Fourier Series has more
than two coefficients.  The somewhat tedious proof uses the orthogonality property
of complex exponential signals.  The general result, known as Parseval&#39;s Theorem is

\begin{align*}\begin{split}
 x(t) &= \sum\limits_{k=-N}^N a_k e^{ j2\pi k f_0 t}\\
  &= a_0+ 2\Re{e}\left\{
  \sum\limits_{k=1}^N a_k e^{ j2\pi k f_0 t}\right\}

 \end{split}\end{align*}

Using the complex exponential representation of the cosines, we
can write <a class="flink bkeq" ref="eq-persumcos"><span ref="eq-persumcos" class="glyphicon glyphicon-option-horizontal" aria-hidden="true"></span></a> as
 <div class="equation" id="eq-persumexp">\(\begin{split}
 x(t) &= \sum\limits_{k=-N}^N a_k e^{ j2\pi k f_0 t}\\
  &= a_0+ 2\Re{e}\left\{
  \sum\limits_{k=1}^N a_k e^{ j2\pi k f_0 t}\right\}

 \end{split}\)</div>
 where \(a_k\) was defined by <a class="flink bkeq" ref="eq-ak-defined"><span ref="eq-ak-defined" class="glyphicon glyphicon-option-horizontal" aria-hidden="true"></span></a>
  in Section~<a class="flink bkimg" ref="sec-ak-notation">&#8251;</a>.

